[normal]Written evidence submitted by [bold]T[bold]he Football Association[bold] (The FA)[bold] [WAS0030][bold]&#xa0;[bold]Introduction[bold]&#xa0;[bold]1.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The Football Association is the national governing body responsible for football in England. The FA’s remit is to support, govern and develop the game from the grassroots through to the professional game. The FA runs 24 national teams (which 
[normal]include,
[normal] men’s
[normal], women’s, youth and disability teams) and its own competitions such as the Women’s Super League and The FA Cup
[normal] as well as owning and operating Wembley Stadium and St. George’s Park.
[normal] As a not-for-profit organisation, The FA uses revenue created by the Engl
[normal]and teams
[normal], The FA Cup
[normal] and Wembley Stadium to reinvest into the game and run grassroots football. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The FA took over Women’s 
[normal]football
[normal] in 1993
[normal] and we 
[normal]are
[normal] celebrat
[normal]ing
[normal] our 20
[normal]th
[normal] anniversary in 2013. 
[normal]Women’s football is now England’s 
[normal]third biggest team sport
[normal] in its own right (after men's football and men's cricket) according to Sport England’s Active People Survey. T
[normal]here 
[normal]are now 
[normal]over 1
[normal],
[normal]400 adult women's club teams, over 3,500 girls’ club teams, 138 female disability teams
[normal], 28,000 qualified female coaches
[normal] and 
[normal]944 registered and active 
[normal]female 
[normal]referees
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The FA launched its Game Changer 5-year strategy for women’s football in October 2012. This will deliver a new Elite Performance Unit, a new commercial strategy, a second tier to supp
[normal]ort The FA Women’s Super 
[normal]League
[normal], growth in participation and growth of the fan-base. The FA has committed 
[normal]through this plan 
[normal]to a further £3.5m investment into women’s football in the ne
[normal]xt 5
[normal] years. This adds to the total investment from The FA and its funding partners which this se
[normal]ason exceeded £11m.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Despite th
[normal]is
[normal] 
[normal]successful 
[normal]growth and development of the women’s game, The FA is working hard to continue to progress the game at all levels. Likewise Government can also help in the game’s evolution and a number of suggestions are includ
[normal]ed in this paper. 
